pull_request.title: Add a test workflow
pull_request.body:
This PR adds a workflow that does nothing but run the Github Action once on the branch that triggers the code run. This it to make it possible to see what future code changes do.

This test passes, but that's actually a problem. Since no AWS credentials are provided, this workflow should fail loudly. So having it pass like this means that the code, in its current state, will mask potentially serious problems like not being able to communicate with AWS. 

We do need to fix that before this goes to production, but this PR is to just start us off with a way to run our own code on PR's.

pull_request.title: Add a test workflow
pull_request.body:
This PR adds a workflow that does nothing but run the Github Action once on the branch that triggers the code run. This it to make it possible to see what future code changes do.

This test passes, but that's actually a problem. Since no AWS credentials are provided, this workflow should fail loudly. So having it pass like this means that the code, in its current state, will mask potentially serious problems like not being able to communicate with AWS. 

We do need to fix that before this goes to production, but this PR is to just start us off with a way to run our own code on PR's.

issue.title: Add some testing!
issue.body:
Most of these tests were already in this repo previously, but were deleted. I added them back, but this required a minor refactor of `cache.service.ts` to avoid using a class (JS classes are not that great anyway). Only the tests in `cacheService.test.ts` are new and written by me.
